Comment on a httplib2 implementation detail.

httplib2 rewrites part of the headers when writing the content to the
cache. This is because it doesn't have access to the original
request. Since we are expecting Response objects, we already have the
original request available to peek at.

fragment after the fact or using a hash rather than a specific URL
format.

Add support for ETag logic on GETs

Add configurable httplib2 like etag support.

We're still using ETags by default, which means if we get an ETag, then
we cache it. I think the httplib2 methodology might be better in the
general sense, but I'd like to prove that to be the case rather than
speculate.

In either case, I also think it might be a good idea to be able to turn
off ETag caching completely since it does make deleting from the cache
more difficult. For example, once a request is cached due to an ETag, it
won't be deleted unless the server specifically provides a no-cache
directive. If the cache uses a LRU technique, it will expire on its own,
but if someone uses the default memory cache and is requesting large
files, then we're going to make someone angry with a memory leak.

Maybe add a good LRU memory cache that is limited.

Use sha224 instead of md5 to key the FileCache

MD5 is vulnerable to collision attacks which it may be possible
to use to attack a project using CacheControl. There are no
known theoretical or practical attacks against the sha-2 family of
hash functions so use one of them instead. sha224 is selected due
to the smaller digest size which will be less likely to hit edge
cases in filename sizes.

Use os.open to ensure that files for the cache have correct perms

The previous file handling code suffered from a few issues.

1. It would only create the leaf directory if it didn't exist but
   would error if any parent directories didn't exist. This will
   use os.makedirs to create anything needed.
2. Directories created by FileCache uses the default umask, instead
   we'll make this configurable and make it default to 0700 which
   will prevent any access from anyone but the user who owns the
   process.
3. Files created by FileCache use the default umask, instead we'll
   make this configurable and make it defalt to 0600 so only the
   user who owns the process can read/write them.
4. Following the cache file mode bits above, we'll also ensure that
   we create the files securely to prevent against symlink attacks
   or someone dropping a file with bad permissions before we open
   it.

Serialize the in memory cache to Pickle as well

This is done so that the in memory cache and the file/redis cache

Cache the urllib3 HTTPResponse instead of the requests Response

Enables the use of requests.models.Response().raw by caching the
raw urllib3 HTTPResponse instead of the requests Response. We can
then construct a new Response on each request. This will also
enable things like resp.encoding and the future resp.content_encoding
to work correctly.

Some Notes:
  * Vary headers are currently broken because what we cache no longer
    has access to the request that made it.
  * This is backwards incompatible with the current cache handling
    code, that should be gracefully handled.
  * All requests, streaming or not, are still consumed immediately and
    are now replaced by a io.BytesIO backed HTTPResponse.

Do not monkeypatch requests.model.Response to enable pickle

CacheControl no longer attempts to pickle a requests.model.Response
object so we no longer care if it can be.
Gracefully handle the case where an old object is in the cache

Handle Vary headers

This keeps the existing behavior where a mismatch on the Vary headers
simply acts as a cache miss rather than making it possible to store
multiple responses for different sets of Vary headers. This includes
a change to the logic to properly handle the '*' value in a Vary
header.

Filter out content-length when updating headers on a 304.

Servers should *NOT* be sending this header as the spec states the 304
should only include headers that are valid for a cached value. That
said, no one is perfect and it is easy to inject a content length
throughout a stack.

We'll try to be graceful and strip it out and we can add other
blacklisted items as needed... That is until we want to be strict and
just invalidate the cache b/c the server is wrong. I suspect, being
graceful in light of an incorrect server will serve users better,
especially when they can't fix the server.

Namespace the cache directories

Some file systems limit how many files can be in a single directory,
for projects that cache a lot of responses this could be a problem.

Fixes #56: Add support for 301 and 300

The spec seems to explicitly define what 3xx responses are
cacheable. The 301s are always cached as they are seemingly permanent,
while 300s *may* be cached like any other 200 response.

I suspect the 300 case will not be very common as the spec implied there
was not a clear best practice and defining the URIs was not
consistent. The correct way (according to the spec) is to use multiple
Link headers with a relationship of "alternate", but it sounds like this
is rare.

Don't warn about freshness, as heuristic freshness is capped.

The spec explains when a warning is necessary:

   When a heuristic is used to calculate freshness lifetime, a cache
   SHOULD generate a Warning header field with a 113 warn-code (see
   Section 5.5.4) in the response if its current_age is more than 24
   hours and such a warning is not already present.

As this implementation caps freshness at twenty-four hours, I don't
believe the warning is necessary for this heuristic.

Heuristic freshness shouldn't be used for unknown status codes

early in those cases.

Fix behaviour of Cache-Control: no-store on responses

According to RFC 7234, section 5.2.2.3: Response Cache-Control
Directives, no-store:

"The "no-store" response directive indicates that a cache MUST NOT
store any part of either the immediate request or response.  This
directive applies to both private and shared caches.  "MUST NOT
store" in this context means that the cache MUST NOT intentionally
store the information in non-volatile storage, and MUST make a
best-effort attempt to remove the information from volatile storage
as promptly as possible after forwarding it.[...]"

https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc7234#section-5.2.2.3

The second part ("[...] MUST make a best-effort attempt to
remove the information [...]") was already handled, but if any other
conditions for caching responses became true, for example presence of
Etags, permanent redirect etc. the response was cached even with
Cache-Control: no-store.

This behaviour is fixed by just returning if the no_store flag is set,
potentially after having purged the cache entry.

Make v4 cache compatible with msgpack 1.0 in the future

The `encoding` parameter in `msgpack.loads` is deprecated and will be
removed in msgpack 1.0 [1].

Note that the `raw` parameter was called `raw_as_bytes` before 0.5.2
[2]. I add the version constraint to avoid API incompatibilities.

[1] https://github.com/msgpack/msgpack-python/issues/191
[2] https://github.com/msgpack/msgpack-python/commit/5569a4efcdc913d343eaff4e55c9b19fafde4268

Include HTTP 308 as a permanent redirect.

The new status code was introduced with RFC 7538 in April 2015.

This makes it so that "308 Permanent Redirect" status codes are treated the
same as "301 Moved Permanently" statuses.

Make `Serializer.dumps()` require a `body` parameter.

When caching permanent redirects, if `body` is left to `None`, there's an infinite recursion that will lead to the caching to silently fail and not cache anything at all.

So instead, make `body` a required parameter, which can be empty (`''`) for cached redirects.
